BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:IU Eskenazi School of Art, Architecture + Design
DTSTART:20260910T200000Z
DTEND:20260910T220000Z
LOCATION:SIDNEY AND LOIS ESKENAZI MUSEUM OF ART
GEO:39.169144;-86.519739
SUMMARY:Exhibition Opening Reception for The Photographic Reflex: The Lee
  Marks and John C. DePrez Jr. Collection
DESCRIPTION:Thursday\, September 10\, 20264ŌĆō6 p.m. Opening reception  H
 ors d'oeuvres and cash bar (4ŌĆō6 p.m.)  First floor atrium  About The Ph
 otographic Reflex: The Lee Marks and John C. DePrez Jr. Collection (https
 ://artmuseum.indiana.edu/exhibitions/upcoming/_feature-exhibitions/2026-0
 8-29-photographic-reflex-marks-deprez.html):  Spanning more than 150 year
 s\, The Photographic Reflex celebrates a transformative gift to the IU Es
 kenazi Museum of Art from collectors Lee Marks and John C. DePrez Jr. The
  exhibition features more than one hundred photographs by eighty artists\
 , highlighting the breadth\, power\, and enduring impact of photographic 
 expression.  Photographs dating from 1856 to 2017 reveal photography's du
 al role as both a tool for documentation and a vehicle for artistic explo
 ration. Organized into five thematic sectionsŌĆöPlay of Light\, Industria
 l Eye\, Photographic Figure\, Witness to Conflict\, and Impressed by Natu
 re's HandŌĆöthe exhibition examines how photographers across disciplines 
 have communicated ideas\, recorded history\, and shaped visual culture.  
 The exhibition includes works by many of the most influential figures in 
 the medium\, from Berenice Abbott\, Alfred Stieglitz\, Edward Steichen\, 
 and Henri Cartier-Bresson to contemporary artists such as Edward Burtynsk
 y\, Abelardo Morell\, Susan Derges\, and Vik Muniz.  A richly illustrated
  exhibition catalogue\, featuring an interview with the collectors\, will
  accompany The Photographic Reflex and will be available for purchase thr
 ough the museum's Newkirk Caf├® and Gift Shop.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p><strong>Thursday\, September 10\, 2026</s
 trong></p><p><strong>4ŌĆō6 p.m. Opening reception</strong></p><p>  Hors d
 'oeuvres and cash bar (4ŌĆō6 p.m.)</p><p>  First floor atrium</p><p>  Abo
 ut <i><a href="https://artmuseum.indiana.edu/exhibitions/upcoming/_featur
 e-exhibitions/2026-08-29-photographic-reflex-marks-deprez.html">The Photo
 graphic Reflex: The Lee Marks and John C. DePrez Jr. Collection</a></i>:<
 /p><p>  Spanning more than 150 years\, <i>The Photographic Reflex</i> cel
 ebrates a transformative gift to the IU Eskenazi Museum of Art from colle
 ctors Lee Marks and John C. DePrez Jr. The exhibition features more than 
 one hundred photographs by eighty artists\, highlighting the breadth\, po
 wer\, and enduring impact of photographic expression.</p><p>  Photographs
  dating from 1856 to 2017 reveal photography's dual role as both a tool f
 or documentation and a vehicle for artistic exploration. Organized into f
 ive thematic sectionsŌĆö<i>Play of Light</i>\, <i>Industrial Eye</i>\, <i
 >Photographic Figure</i>\, <i>Witness to Conflict</i>\, and <i>Impressed 
 by Nature's Hand</i>ŌĆöthe exhibition examines how photographers across d
 isciplines have communicated ideas\, recorded history\, and shaped visual
  culture.</p><p>  The exhibition includes works by many of the most influ
 ential figures in the medium\, from Berenice Abbott\, Alfred Stieglitz\, 
 Edward Steichen\, and Henri Cartier-Bresson to contemporary artists such 
 as Edward Burtynsky\, Abelardo Morell\, Susan Derges\, and Vik Muniz.</p>
 <p>  A richly illustrated exhibition catalogue\, featuring an interview w
 ith the collectors\, will accompany <i>The Photographic Reflex</i> and wi
 ll be available for purchase through the museum's Newkirk Caf├® and Gift 
 Shop.</p>
